<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0173</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Association of Colleges – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AoC</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Association of Colleges (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">AoC</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">) represents and promotes the 341 Colleges in England incorporated under the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, including 94 Sixth Form Colleges and 247 Further Education Colleges which:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Educate 853,000 people aged 16 to 18, almost twice as many as school sixth forms. This includes 185,000 young people taking A-levels;</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Train over one quarter of the total 240,000 apprentices aged 16 to 18; </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Educate and train over two million people aged 19 and over;</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Account for 33% of entrants to higher education and for 11% of those studying at undergraduate or higher national (for example, foundation degrees).</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Draft Bill proposes a number of changes in post-16 education and training. We comment on each of these below.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 3 &amp; Schedule 1 – simplification of apprenticeships </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This Clause introduces changes proposed by Doug Richard in his report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> on the future of apprenticeships. Colleges absolutely support the strengthening of apprenticeships and welcome many of the proposals in the Draft Deregulation Bill.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The first part of the simplification relates to the removal of the English certifying authority. The Apprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009 created an authority and then gave the Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">powers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to direct their actions. This role has been carried out by Apprenticeship Certificates England</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> for the last two years. Before the 2009 Act, Sector Skills Councils issued apprenticeship certificates. The Draft Deregulation Bill gives the Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">powers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to issue certificates as he/she wishes or to delegate the function if he/she wishes. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is proposed that the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">law governing the content of the apprenticeship certificate are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to be removed. The 2009 Act required a certificate to name the person, sector, level etc. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Bill also proposes a stripped down approach to standards. The 2009 Act required the Chief Executive of Skills Funding (if directed by the Secretary of State) to issue standards (Specification of Apprenticeship Standards, SASE) for consultation and then implementation and required the issuing authority (the National Apprenticeship Service) to publish frameworks which complied with SASE. The proposed new rules </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">allow the Secretary of State to “prepare and publish standards for such sectors of work as the Secretary of State thinks appropriate”. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Section 23 (2) of the 2009 Act required the Chief Executive of Skills Funding to consult with employers, institutions within FE sector (as defined by Education Act 2006) and other providers about the approved apprenticeship standards. The Draft Deregulation Bill gives power for employers (or representative of employers) to make proposals as to the content of the apprenticeship standard, which we fully support. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that these proposals will simplify the apprenticeship approval process for employers and allow them to develop </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> faster than before because they will only need to secure sign-off from the Secretary of State. However, we are concerned that this </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">centralises</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> control with no legal safeguards to ensure that there is a period of consultation or reflection. The risk here is that an employer could invent an apprenticeship which is of lower standard than an existing certificate and that Government officials advising the Secretary of State may not be able to properly assess it because of the speed of the process. We will be looking for assurances from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that protections</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> will be in place to prevent this.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We also believe that it would be helpful for those providing the education and training, which forms part of an apprenticeship, to have the same power to suggest changes to the content of apprenticeship standards that Clause 23 (2) gives to employers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 31 &amp; Schedule 12 – abolition of the statutory post of Chief Executive of Skills Funding</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This Clause fulfils the ambition of bringing the Chief Executive of Skills Funding more directly under the remit of BIS with the statutory functions transferring to the Secretary of State. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that this proposal will simplify the relationship between BIS and the Skills Funding Agency which will become an executive agency rather than an organization led via a statutory corporate position. There will be little immediate effect on Colleges or their students, apprentices and employers that they serve but there is a small risk that this </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">centralises</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> power in a Minister who also, from 1 September 2013, takes on the role of charitable regulator of Colleges. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">AoC</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> is comfortable that BIS has processes that ensure proper decision-making on issues relating to the creation, regulation and closure of Colleges but we think it may be necessary for the Select Committee to have a watching brief on this issue to ensure that the new powers are used appropriately.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 32 &amp; Schedule 13 – amendments to the Further and Higher Education Act 1992 including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Removal of the need for principals and staff to be qualified</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Removal of the Secretary of State’s power to convert a sixth form college into an FE College (although they can still voluntarily convert)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Repeals original clauses needed for to remove colleges from local authority control in 1993</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">As the employers’ association for FE Colleges, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">AoC</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> believes that the continued provision of outstanding teaching and learning in Colleges will require </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">staff that are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> appropriately qualified. Most colleges will want to identify this as a requirement in the vast majority of their employment contracts but like universities, Colleges can be trusted to appoint the right staff and support their professional development without the need for statutory regulation. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">With the revocation of statutory regulation we expect the new Education and Training Foundation to provide proper support and guidance to colleges and their staff in obtaining appropriate qualifications and continuous professional development.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We support repeal of the Secretary of State’s power to change a sixth form college into an FE College and of the original clauses needed to remove colleges from local authority control. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt"> http://www.schoolforstartups.co.uk/richard-review/richard-review-full.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt"> The ACE online system is the place where apprentices, or</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt">third parties</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:10pt">acting on their behalf, apply for their Apprenticeship certificates.</span></p></body></html>